 Cumberland, England","Workington, Cumberland, England":"Workington, Cumberland, England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England"},"en":{"1350–about 1395":"1350–about 1395","1350–1395":"1350–1395","–1386":"–1386","1350–1403":"1350–1403","–Male":"Deceased","1382–1453":"1382–1453","–1441":"–1441","1403":"1403","1453":"1453","1441":"1441","1386":"1386","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","about 1365":"about 1365","before 1382":"before 1382","1382":"1382","before 1380":"before 1380","about 1395":"about 1395","Drumburgh Castle, Cumberland, England":"Drumburgh, Cumberland, England","Workington, Cumberland, England":"Workington, Cumberland, England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Brun","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Normand, Patrice, Philippe, Pierre, Thierry, Armand, Georges, Henri, Jean Michael, Jean-Marc, Lorette, Lucien.","French, Catalan, and Scandinavian; North German (also <b>Brün</b>): nickname from French and Catalan <i>brun</i>, Middle Low German <i>brūn</i> ‘brown’, referring to the color of the hair, complexion, or clothing. As a surname of French origin it is also found in Haiti. Compare French   Lebrun   and German   Bruen  .","North German, Scandinavian, and Dutch: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Brun(o)</i>, from <i>brūna</i> ‘brown’. See also   Braun  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Brunell","meanings":["English (Lancashire): nickname denoting someone with a brownish complexion, from Middle English <i>burnel</i>, a metathesized form of Old French <i>brunel</i>, a diminutive of Old French <i>brun</i> ‘brown’; used also as a personal name.","Swedish: ornamental name from <i>brun</i> ‘brown’ + the suffix <i>-ell</i>, a derivative of the Latin adjectival ending <i>-elius</i>.","German (also <b>Brünell</b>): nickname meaning ‘brown’ (see   Brun  )."]},{"name":"Breunig","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Florian, Franz, Math, Siegfried, Winfried.","German: from the old personal name <i>Brūning</i>, a derivative of <i>Brun(o)</i> (see   Brun  ), which was diphthongized (via <i>Brüning</i>; see   Bruning   2) to <i>Breuni(n)g</i> in the 17th century."]},{"name":"Brauning","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gernot, Gunther, Helmut.","South German (<b>Bräuning</b>): patronymic from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Brun(o)</i> (see   Brun  )."]},{"name":"Bruneau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Patrice, Alcide, Amie, Andre, Arianne, Armand, Cecile, Emile, Jean-Claude, Lucien, Napoleon.","French: diminutive of   Brun   ‘brown’. Compare   Bronaugh  .","History: Pierre-Guillaume Bruneau <i>dit</i> Pelletier, from Poitiers, married Marie-Élisabeth Morin in Quebec City, QC, in 1758. Joseph Petit <i>dit</i> Bruneau from Paris, France, married Marie Chenay in Quebec City, QC, in 1675. — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Breun","meanings":["(2010: NA)","German: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Bruno</i>, see   Brun  ."]},{"name":"Bruner","meanings":["German: nickname from Old High German, Old Saxon <i>Brūn</i> (see   Brun  ).","German and Jewish: variant of   Brunner  ."]},{"name":"Bruhn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Hans, Bernd, Bernhard, Dieter, Kurt, Gerhard, Heinz, Johann, Wolfgang.","North German (also <b>Brühn</b>), Danish, and Swedish: variant of   Brun  ."]},{"name":"Braun","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Ernst, Otto, Alois, Gerhard, Helmut, Fritz, Heinz, Joerg, Wolfgang, Egon.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname from German <i>braun</i> ‘brown’ (Middle High German <i>brūn</i>), referring to the color of the hair, complexion, or clothing.","German: from the personal name <i>Bruno</i>, which was borne by the Dukes of Saxony, among others, from the 10th century or before. It was also the name of several medieval German and Italian saints, including Saint Bruno, the founder of the Carthusian order (1030–1101), who was born in Cologne. See also   Brun  ."]},{"name":"Brunel","meanings":["French: diminutive of   Brun   ‘brown’. Compare   Brunelle  .","History: Jacques Brunel from Dieppe in Seine-Maritime, France, married Suzanne Bertault in Boucherville, QC, in 1677."]},{"name":"Lebrun","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Fernand, Normand, Andre, Emile, Herve, Lucien, Michel, Yves, Adelard, Dominique, Edouard.","French and Walloon: variant of   Brun   ‘brown’, with fused masculine definite article <i>le</i>."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into 